<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Flocculation" class="currentChild" href="Flocculation">Flocculation</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
An ink problem characterized by particles of <a title="Pigment" href="Pigment">pigment</a> becoming "undispersed" and "flocking" together in clumps, commonly caused by the addition of a substance that "shocks" the particles out of suspension. Ink that has undergone flocculation tends to print with decreased <a title="Color Strength" href="Color_Strength">color strength</a>, and occasionally with decreased <a title="Gloss" href="Gloss">gloss</a>. Adding <a title="Solvent" href="Solvent">solvent</a> to the ink may help alleviate the problem, although adding an excessive amount of solvent will result in an excessive decrease in <a title="Viscosity" href="Viscosity">viscosity</a>. (See also <a title="Sedimentation" href="Sedimentation">Sedimentation</a>.) The dispersion of clustered pigment particles is called <a title="Deflocculation" href="Deflocculation">deflocculation</a>. 
</p>
